                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="ogtnotes">
                    
                        <note n="1" xml:id="ogt_1">
                            
<p xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance">Invitation to Van Rappard to come to Nuenen <ref target="let441.xml">(441)</ref></p>
                        </note>
                        
                            

                        
                    
                </listAnnotation>
                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="notes">
                    
                        <note n="1" xml:id="note-t-1">
                            

<p>Theo was 27 on 1 May 1884.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="2" xml:id="note-t-2">
                            

<p>This remark must refer to the payment of Theo’s share in the profits for 1883 at <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_797">Boussod, Valadon &amp; Cie</rs>. From the ‘Compte de Monsieur Van Gogh’ (<rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_526">Mr van Gogh</rs>’s account) it emerges that he was paid the sum of 8226.80 francs on 21 April 1884 (FR b2124). Normally Theo received advances plus extra ‘remittances’ over and above them; cf. in this connection for the year 1889: <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">Account book </hi>2002, p. 41. See also <ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let479.xml#n-2">letter 479, n. 2.</ref></p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="3" xml:id="note-t-3">
                            

<p>Most probably <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">Weaver</hi> (<rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_2467">F 30 / JH 479</rs>), which is indeed ‘fairly large’: it measures 70 x 85 cm. Later Van Gogh had it photographed: <ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let463.xml">see letters 463</ref> and <ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let465.xml">465</ref>.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="4" xml:id="note-t-4">
                            

<p>
      <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">Weaver and a spinning wheel</hi> (<rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_2462">F 29 / JH 471</rs>), discussed in <ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let440.xml">letter 440</ref>.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="5" xml:id="note-t-5">
                            

<p>We do not know which two paintings of ‘effects on the heath’ he is referring to here.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="6" xml:id="note-t-6">
                            

<p>
      <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">Landscape with pollard birches</hi> (<rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_2466">F 31 / JH 477</rs>).</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="7" xml:id="note-t-7">
                            

<p>This plan probably resulted in the paintings <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">Weaver arranging threads</hi> (<rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#noill_554">F 35 / JH 478</rs>) and <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">Weaver arranging threads</hi> (<rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#noill_555">F 32 / JH 480</rs>).</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="8" xml:id="note-t-8">
                            
      
<p>See for the engraving after <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1226">Jean-François Millet</rs>, <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics"><rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_1682">La veillée</rs></hi> (Evening) from the series <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">The four times of the day</hi>, which Van Gogh owned: <ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let037.xml#n-16">letter 37, n. 16</ref>. The painting was at the Sale <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1790">Gavet</rs> at Hôtel Drouot which Van Gogh had been to in 1875: <ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let036.xml#n-5">see letter 36, n. 5.</ref> The lamp casting light on the family in this scene bears some resemblance to the sketched model.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                            

                        
                    
